                        "content": "Assessment and diagnostic evaluation reveal that a client seen in the ambulatory care clinic has stage II Lyme disease. The clinic nurse identifies which assessment finding as most characteristic of this stage?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "11797937e327eb6d913faa80427c566b",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Analyzing 分析",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nLyme disease is a reportable systemic infectious disease caused by the spirochete Borellia burgdorferi and results from the bite of an infected deer tick, also known as the black-legged tick. Stage II of Lyme disease develops within 1 to 6 months in a majority of untreated persons. The most serious problems include cardiac conduction deficits and neurological disorders such as Bell's palsy and paralysis. Arthralgias and joint enlargement are noted in stage III. A rash appears in stage I.",
                        "id": "ed7cafebda2a4655a90e73bbd6f644a0",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "0c3e25ed5c33407ab33e749b8a9eb0d5",
                                "content": "Tell the client that testing is not necessary unless arthralgia develops."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "d5755f3dd7224ecd82ba1c3082c54eb0",
                                "content": "Tell the client to avoid any woody, grassy areas that may contain ticks."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "e86e8db0cea5432f888600ec20d36178",
                                "content": "Instruct the client to immediately start to take the antibiotics that are prescribed."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "1",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "62cc36ef7b4a40d7ae514edce2baab49",
                                "content": "Inform the client to plan to have a blood test 4 to 6 weeks after a bite to detect the presence of the disease."
                            },
                            {
                                "isRight": "0",
                                "userAnswer": "",
                                "isSelected": "0",
                                "id": "13f497911bc44c978028eead4040ef15",
                                "content": "Tell the client that if this happens again, to never remove the tick but to vigorously scrub the area with an antiseptic."
                            }
                        ],
